body:
Add the support both for sequential and non-sequential UDP.  Take the following example to show how to realize the algorithm. The mix udp example is:
```
primitive d_edge_ff (q, clock, data, reset);
 output q; reg q;
 input clock, data, reset;
 initial q = 1'b1;
 table
     // clock data reset q q+
     (01) 0 0 : ? : 0 ;
     (01) 1 0 : ? : 1 ;
     (10) 0 0 : ? : 1 ;
     (10) 1 0 : ? : 0 ;
      ?  1 1 : ? : 0 ;
      ?  0 1 : ? : 0 ;
 endtable
endprimitive
```
There are both sequential parts and non-sequential parts. The basic idea is that contact all the input signals:
inputSig = {clock, data, reset];
Then another two signals maskSig and cmpSig are used to confirm whether the condition for every line of the table is satisfied. The conditon is "inputSig & maskSig == cmpSig", for line1 "(01) 0 0 " of the table above, maskSig = "111" and cmpSig = "100". For line  5  "?  1 1",  maskSig = "011" and cmpSig = "011". 
Both sequential parts and non-sequential parts are realized by always block.
